[["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[1]/text()[1]","Itâ€™s 6:30 a.m.Â as I arrive at Green Haven, a maximum security prison in Dutchess County."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[2]/text()[1]","I lock my cellphone in my vehicle because even if I bring it in with me accidently, I will be suspended without pay and face disciplinary action."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[3]/text()[1]","As I enter the facility, I must open my lunch container and show it to the officer to verify that I have not brought in any contraband.Â I have to bring lunch because I have no other access to food where I work.Â The steel door closes and the outside world becomes nothing but a memory for a minimum of 8 and Â¼ hours."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[4]/text()[1]","I report to a unit that houses 264 inmates, and I am responsible for overseeing 88 of them. Most of the inmates in this facility are murderers, rapists, armed robbers and major drug dealers.Â There are no pleasantries as I make my rounds like most workers experience at their place of work."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[5]/text()[1]","As I walk passed their cells, some inmates wonâ€™t make eye contact and some make remarks about my physical appearance in an attempt to intimidate me. This game is played all day long, every day â€” Iâ€™ve built up a pretty thick skin over the last 22 years. As I escort the inmates to the mess hall, I wait for the gate to open and then direct them in, counting them to ensure that I have the same number of inmates that I left the block with. I keep a constant watch on them to ensure no fights or passing contraband. After they eat and I return them to their cells, I report to my next assignment."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[6]/text()[1]","Standing in the yard with only one other officer and more than 400 inmates is extremely stressful.Â An incident can occur unexpectedly â€” like a stabbing, a fight or worse. An inmate could decide that I had disrespected him in front of other inmates and stab me with a sharpened metal shank. Or an inmate that I had to discipline two months prior because I found him extorting other inmates could decide to exact his revenge by pushing me from behind into the steel bars face first, fracturing my orbital socket."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[7]/text()[1]","I patrol the yard, my head on a swivel, constantly observing the inmates. The yard self-separates by factions: White, Black, Muslim, Aryan, Bloods, Crips.Â They all seem to have their own section of the yard."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[8]/text()[1]","I have been involved in incidents where I was assaulted, where Iâ€™ve responded to assaults on staff and where Iâ€™ve responded to inmate fights."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[9]/text()[1]","Iâ€™ve seen firsthand fellow corrections officers with their faces beaten beyond recognition, an officer who had hot oil thrown in his face and stabbed several times, and a supervisor who was stabbed several times by an inmate with weapons tied to his hands. Iâ€™ve seen inmates die from stab wounds, drug overdoses and illness right in front of me. Iâ€™ve dug through human feces with tongue depressors looking for contraband that an inmate swallowed earlier in the day."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[10]/text()[1]","But, worst of all, Iâ€™ve had several fellow officers commit suicide over the years.Â We are under constant scrutiny by the department and routinely subjected to grievances by inmates when we enforce the laws of New York state."],["/html[1]/body[1]/div[1]/div[2]/article[1]/div[3]/p[11]/text()[1]","Thankfully, my day ends without any incident. I am able to go home in one piece and come back tomorrow for another shift. As I leave, I wonder if any of the officers reporting for duty might turn out to be one of the 747 that were assaulted last year â€” a record high.Â I hope that their tour might turn out to be like mine, without violence, but I know thatâ€™s not very likely. Those are the realities of being a New York State Corrections Officer."]]